#Text=Cavite City
#Text=Cavite City
#Text=is a city in Cavite in the Philippines .
#Text=Understand
#Text=This article covers only the city proper ; Corregidor Island , administratively part of Cavite City is practically covered in a separate page .
#Text=Cavite
#Text=City lies at the hook-shaped peninsula that lends Cavite province its name .

#Text=Until the Spaniards constructed a causeway as a permanent link to the rest of Cavite , most of the peninsula is a sandbar , which becomes flooded during high tide and also pose a risk for ships , and Cavite City , then a town , virtually turns into a an island .
#Text=The population is around 103,000 , as of 2015 .
#Text=History
#Text=Cavite City has its share of historical charms , and was the capital of Cavite until it is transfer to Trece Martires .

#Text=It is established as a town since its discovery by Miguel López de Legazpi , and at the midst of Spanish colonial rule , Cavite , then called Cavite La Punta , served as an important point for the Manila- Acapulco galleons , and serves as the de facto Port of Manila because of the sandbank that prevents ships from entering the mouth of the Pasig River .
#Text=As the town grew , Cavite since ceded four independent towns , like San Roque , La Caridad , San Antonio , Santa Cruz , and Dalahican , which remain as barangays .
#Text=The Spaniards built a causeway over the sandbank to connect the town with mainland Cavite , but erosion reduced this to an isthmus ; the causeway remains today as part of Manila-Cavite Road .
#Text=During American occupation , Corregidor Island and other smaller islands are added to the city , and the Port of Cavite is converted into a US Navy station , Naval Station Sangley Point .
#Text=Cavite gained city status in 1940 , one year before World War II broke out in the Pacific .
#Text=Cavite City is devastated by the 1945 Allied bombings ; Sangley Point , the walls of Porta Vaga , and the old town is badly destroyed by bombs .
#Text=Most damaged structures are required to be demolished , and only a few remains of the old Port of Cavite .
#Text=Orientation
#Text=Cavite City is small , and its street layout has hardly changed since the Spanish colonial era .
#Text=It is divided into 17 barangays ; the most important being San Roque , which houses the city hall , plaza and Fort San Felipe .
#Text=Talk
#Text=Cavite City is one of the few places where the Spanish creole language Chavacano is still spoken by most of the population .
#Text=The variety of Chavacano spoken here is different from what you may encounter at Zamboanga City , with a different way of indicating verb tense and a distinct set of pronouns .
#Text=Some local businesses have been promoting Chavacano through signs .
#Text=Tagalog is either spoken as a first or second language , and is the lingua franca .
#Text=English is spoken and understood by many locals , and most signs are in English .
#Text=Get in
#Text=Cavite City lies at the western end of Manila-Cavite Road ( Route 62 ) ; it is 30 minutes from Manila by car .
#Text=By plane
#Text=Sangley Point Airport
#Text=( SGL ) .
#Text=Under construction and expected to open by October 2019
#Text=, this airport is being built at the present site of Danilo Atienza Air Base and utilizing its current runway , except for some lengthening work to accommodate narrow-body jets .
#Text=This new airport is expected to receive flights on low-cost carriers , air charters , and general aviation .
#Text=Until the expected opening of Sangley Point Airport , the nearest airport with regular flights is Ninoy Aquino International Airport ( NAIA ) , which is about from the city .
#Text=From NAIA , you can take a taxi , bus or jeepney to the bus station in Parañaque , or just take the taxi .
#Text=If you arrive on an international flight , they will always touch down at NAIA ( the future airport has a runway too short for wide-body jets ) .
#Text=By bus
#Text=Saint Anthony of Padua Transport
#Text=and Saulog Transport provides service from Manila ( Park N ' Ride ) or Parañaque ( PITX ) to their terminals in Cavite City .
#Text=You can also hop onto the colorful but cramped minibuses ( " baby buses " ) from Baclaran in Parañaque or Bacoor .
#Text=Saint Anthony of Padua Transport
#Text=.
#Text=Most trips depart from PITX , but some still continue to Park N ' Ride ( or " Lawton " in signs ) and Santa Cruz in Manila .
#Text=Saulog Transport
#Text=, Dra .
#Text=Salamanca Street .
#Text=Services leave every 30 minutes from Parañaque Integrated Transport Exchange .
#Text=Tricycles are available from outside the terminal .
#Text=By ferry
#Text=MRS Super Shuttle
#Text=Provides ferry boat service between Cavite City and SM Mall of Asia .
#Text=Boats depart Cavite City M - F at 6:30AM , 9AM , 1:30PM and 5PM , and from Mall of Asia every 7:45AM , 11AM , 3PM , and 6:30PM .
#Text=Services from Cavite City leave Sa Su and holidays at 8AM , 10:15AM , 1:30PM and 5PM , and from Mall of Asia departs at 9AM , 11:15AM , 3PM and 6:30PM .
#Text=₱80 ( ₱68 for students , ₱64 for seniors ) .
#Text=See
#Text=Thirteen Martyrs Monument

#Text=, intersection of M. Valentin St. , Lopez Jaena Rd , Zulueta Rd and the P. Burgos Ave. The thirteen Martyrs of Cavite were Filipino patriots executed by musketry on September 12 , 1896 , for cooperating with the Katipunan during the Philippine Revolution against Spain .
#Text=The capital city of Trece Martires in Cavite is named after them .
#Text=In 1906 , a monument to the Thirteen Martyrs was erected at the San Roque district of Cavite City , at the head of then San Roque causeway .
#Text=Their families reinterred the remains of their loved ones at the foot of the monument .
#Text=Fort San Felipe
#Text=( Inside Naval Station Pascual Ledesma ) . Built in 1609 , it served as the fortress for the then town of Cavite , but only half of it remains .
#Text=As an active naval base , permission is required to visit this fort .
#Text=Sangley Point
#Text=.
#Text=Former United States Navy station , since turned over to the Philippine Navy and Philippine Air Force .
#Text=It presently houses the Danilo Atienza Air Base and Naval Base Cavite ; visitors must register first before entering .
#Text=It is also the site of the future Sangley Point Airport ( see #Get in )
#Text=Heroes Arch
#Text=.
#Text=A monumental arch that served as the entrance to the Spanish-era Port of Cavite .
